SIMPLE: operative
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Operative
<hw>Op"er*a*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf.L.
<ets>operativus</ets>, F. <ets>op⟦eacute⟧ratif</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Having the power of acting; hence, exerting force, physical or
moral; active in the production of effects; <as>as, an
<ex>operative</ex> motive; <ex>operative</ex> laws</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It holds in all <qex>operative</qex> principles.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Producing the appropriate or designed effect;
efficacious; effective; <as>as, an <ex>operative</ex> dose, rule, or
penalty</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>Based upon, or consisting of, an
operation or operations; <as>as, <ex>operative</ex>
surgery</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Operative</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Operative
<hw>Op"er*a*tive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A skilled worker;
an artisan; esp., one who operates a machine in a mill or
manufactory.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who acts as an agent of another, especially a
detective or spy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Operatively</ent>⟦br⟧
